    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "In order to avoid redundant definitions I started using the technique described in [this stack overflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62448946/creating-a-numpy-datatype-from-cython-struct). It works for the most part but generates incorrect dtypes in two cases that I have tried.\r\n\r\n```cython\r\nimport numpy as np\r\n\r\nctypedef struct metrics_t:\r\n    float metric1\r\n    float metric2\r\n\r\ncdef metrics_t met\r\nMETRICS_DTYPE = np.asarray(<metrics_t[:1]>(&met)).dtype\r\n```\r\nIn this case `METRICS_DTYPE` will incorrectly be set to `dtype('complex64')` instead of the correct structured dtype. If I use `double` instead of `float`, it is `dtype('complex128')`.\r\n\r\nIf I instead define the struct with a third element like\r\n```cython\r\nctypedef struct metrics_t:\r\n    float metric1\r\n    float metric2\r\n    char  dummy\r\n```\r\nI get the correct structured dtype\r\n`dtype({'names': ['metric1', 'metric2', 'dummy'], 'formats': ['<f4', '<f4', 'S1'], 'offsets': [0, 4, 8], 'itemsize': 12})`.\r\n\r\nAny clue what could be the problem here?",
    "closed_at": null,
